## First Quarter Documentation Updates

Working through the M-3 findings from Day 71 against this framework:

---

### Finding M-001 (Tomcat CVE) — Monitoring Log + POA&M Close

**Update tier:** Tier 1/2 (monitoring log entry for the remediation; POA&M item M-001 closed)

**Monitoring log entry:** [date] — CVE-[number] in Tomcat [version] identified by Inspector. Exploitability assessed: low (Tomcat manager disabled, WAF blocking manager paths). Remediation plan: test environment update [date], production update [date]. Completion: production update applied [date], Inspector re-scan confirmed patched version. POA&M item M-001 closed.

**SSP update required?** No — the Tomcat version change is a patch, not a control implementation change. The control descriptions for SI-2 (Flaw Remediation) and CM-7 (Least Functionality) remain accurate.

**POA&M update:** Item M-001 — Status changed from Open to Closed. Remediation date: [date]. Evidence: Inspector scan showing patched version, monitoring log entry.

---

### Finding M-002 (IAM Password Policy Drift) — SSP Monitoring Note + CM-3 Update

**Update tier:** Tier 3 (SSP update — not to the password policy description, which was correct, but to the CM-3 implementation description)

**The password policy itself was corrected immediately. The SSP's IA-5 implementation description remained accurate throughout — the system was misconfigured for a few days, but the SSP's documented standard (12 characters) was correct. No IA-5 SSP update needed.**

**What does need an SSP update:** The CM-3 implementation description. The finding revealed that the CM-3 ISSO notification procedure is not consistently followed for IAM policy modifications. The SSP's CM-3 implementation description documents what the change management process requires; if the process is not working as documented, the SSP's implementation description is either inaccurate (it says notification happens, but it does not always happen) or needs to be supplemented with the process improvement.

**SSP CM-3 update:** Implementation description updated to add: "IAM policy modifications (including account policy, user policies, and role policies) are included in the ISSO-notification change category. An EventBridge automated notification rule for IAM CreateUser and CreateRole events is in place [reference Day 62 remediation]. An analogous automated notification rule for IAM policy modification events (iam:UpdateAccountPasswordPolicy, iam:PutUserPolicy) will be implemented by [target date] to supplement the procedural notification requirement." This creates a documented gap acknowledgment and remediation commitment in the SSP implementation description itself.

**POA&M update:** New item — CM-3 EventBridge expansion for IAM policy modification events. Owner: IT Administrator. Target: 30 days.

**Monitoring log entry:** [date] — Config NON_COMPLIANT finding for iam-password-policy. Root cause: unauthorized change. Immediate remediation applied. SSP CM-3 updated. POA&M item added for EventBridge expansion.

---

### Finding M-003 (Backup RTO Trend) — POA&M Update + SSP Flag

**Update tier:** Tier 2/3 (POA&M new item; SSP CP-9 implementation description updated with trend note)

**POA&M update:** New item M-003 — CP-9 restoration procedure optimization. Owner: IT Administrator. Target: 60 days. Description: quarterly restoration test RTO of 3:47 — within 4-hour target but narrowing margin. Procedure updated for S3 export format compatibility. Restoration procedure optimization or RTO revision required before data volume growth threatens target compliance.

**SSP update:** CP-9 implementation description updated with a note: "Quarterly restoration test results are tracked in the monitoring log. Most recent test: [date], completion time [3:47], RTO target 4 hours — met. Data volume growth trend indicates restoration procedure optimization review required within 60 days (see POA&M item M-003)." This creates a forward reference from the SSP to the POA&M item, so the SSP accurately reflects the current implementation status including known improvement needs.

---

### Finding M-004 (Internal Role Change Gap) — SSP Update + New POA&M Item

**Update tier:** Tier 3 (SSP update to AC-2 implementation description; new POA&M item)

**SSP AC-2 update:** Implementation description updated to add: "ISSO notification is required for all job function changes that affect required system access levels, including internal transfers between departments and role changes within the organization. The HR and department manager notification process will be updated to include ISSO notification for role changes affecting OpenMRS access (see POA&M item M-004)."

This is an important SSP update: the prior AC-2 implementation description covered account provisioning and deactivation but did not explicitly address the access implications of internal role changes. The finding revealed that this lifecycle stage was undocumented, which is itself a gap — the SSP should describe the complete account management lifecycle, not just the endpoints.

**POA&M update:** New item M-004 — HR/department manager role-change ISSO notification process. Owner: Health IT Manager + ISSO. Target: 45 days.

---

### Finding M-005 (HC3 Threat Briefing) — Monitoring Log + Threat Assessment Update

**Update tier:** Tier 1 (monitoring log entry); risk register update (not an SSP update, but a risk register update reflecting the current threat intelligence)

**Monitoring log entry:** [date] — HC3 briefing reviewed. Healthcare ransomware targeting organizations matching MyClinic profile. Current controls evaluated: MFA enforcement adequate against credential theft vector. Email security posture gap noted for next quarterly review.

**Risk register update:** RS-004 (Ransomware/EHR Unavailability — from Day 38 risk register) updated: current threat intelligence confirms elevated likelihood for organizations matching MyClinic's profile. Likelihood rating reviewed — maintaining current rating but noting HC3 briefing as new supporting evidence. Risk register version updated.

**SSP update required?** No — the threat environment change does not affect the current control implementation descriptions. If the email security gap review produces a finding that requires a new control, that will trigger an SSP update.

