## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The logging-disabled example in the original Day 72 content — "the SSP says we log access to patient data, but logging was disabled during a patch and never turned back on" — is not hypothetical. The **2014 Community Health Systems breach** involved attackers who maintained persistent access to systems for approximately five months before detection. Post-breach forensic analysis found logging gaps that limited the investigators' ability to reconstruct the full extent of what had been accessed.

While the CHS breach had multiple contributing factors, the documentation and monitoring gap theme is directly relevant: organizations that cannot confidently answer "is our logging actually enabled right now?" because their SSP reflects a configuration from months ago are not just at risk of audit findings — they are at risk of being unable to scope a breach when one occurs.

An ISSO who receives a 2am incident notification and opens the SSP to understand what audit trail exists for patient record access needs to find an accurate answer in the SSP, not a six-month-old description. Task M-4 is what makes that possible. The 15 minutes spent updating the SSP's AU-2 entry when a logging configuration change is made is the investment that pays off at 2am during an incident.

